      <div source="bib:Barth1903_01" type="translation" xml:lang="fra">
        <p n="1" rend="stanza">Lui, qui<gap reason="lost"/> fils de Śrī Vīravarman <supplied reason="subaudible">et</supplied> nullement inférieur en puissance, bien que le plus jeune frère de Śrī Bhavavarman ;</p>
        <p n="2" rend="stanza">Lui, Śrī Citrasena, qui possède toutes les marques de la majesté, a pris le nom de Śrī Mahendravarman lors de son sacre.</p>
        <p n="3" rend="stanza">Après avoir conquis toute la contrée, il a, sur ce mont, établi ce liṅga de Giriśa comme le signe de sa victoire.</p>
      </div>
      <div resp="part:kuch" type="translation">
        <!-- The translation is to be revised after checking the identical inscriptions. -->
        <p n="1" rend="stanza">Grandson of Śrī Sārvabhauma <supplied reason="subaudible">and</supplied> son of Śrī Vīravarman, in spite of being the youngest brother of Śrī Bhavavarman <supplied reason="subaudible">he was</supplied> not inferior in power.</p>
        <p n="2" rend="stanza">He whose mark was well known <supplied reason="explanation">
            <foreign>āhatalakṣaṇaḥ</foreign>
          </supplied> previously by name Śrī Citrasena received Śrī Mahendravarman as a name created <supplied reason="subaudible">at the time of his</supplied> enthronement.</p>
        <p n="3" rend="stanza">Having conquered this entire country, <supplied reason="subaudible">he</supplied> installed on the mountain here a <foreign>liṅga</foreign> of Giriśa as his insignia of victory.</p>
      </div>
      <div type="commentary">
        <p>The three stanzas of this inscription are identical to those of five inscriptions, viz. K. 496, K. 497, K. 508, K. 1106 and K. 1190.</p>
        <!-- There is another identical inscription Ka 218 but it is not fully identified for the time being. -->
        <p>The first two stanzas of this inscription are identical to those of five inscriptions, viz. K. 509, K. 1102, K. 1174, K. 1339 and K. 1340.</p>
        <p>The first stanza of this inscription is identical to that of inscriptions K. 1173 and K. 1341.</p>
        <p>The restitution of the <foreign>pāda</foreign> a of the first stanza is based on K. 496, K. 508, K. 509, K. 1102, K. 1106, K. 1173, K. 1174, K. 1339 and K. 1340 ; the stanza in K. 497, K. 1190 and K. 1341 is fragmentary.</p>
      </div>
